# The AI Council
## Multi-Model Synthesis Architecture for AI-Assisted Decision Making

**Date conceived:** 2025 (predates this documentation)
**Author:** Bryan Robert Horsfield
**Status:** Prior art declaration — working implementation exists

---

## Core Concept

A single AI model is a single perspective. One set of training
assumptions. One tendency. One blind spot.

The most important decisions humans make are not made by one
person. They are made in rooms — with specialists, challengers,
researchers, strategists. That structure exists because
single-perspective decisions are fragile.

The AI Council applies this principle to AI:

Multiple models. Same session. Same context. Each contributing
what it does best. Synthesis happens in the session — not in
the user's head.

---

## The Problem Being Solved

Current AI usage pattern:
- User opens one model
- Asks a question
- Gets one perspective
- Opens another model
- Re-explains context
- Gets another perspective
- Manually synthesises the responses

The user is the integration layer. The user does the work
the tools were supposed to do.

The AI Council moves synthesis into the session.

---

## The Architecture

### Single Question → Council Session

User submits a task or question once.
Context is shared across all council members simultaneously.
No re-briefing. No context loss between models.

### Specialist Roles

Each model in the council has a defined role:
- **Lead specialist** — primary domain expert, answers first
- **Analyst** — adds rigour, data, structure
- **Challenger** — finds what was missed, questions assumptions
- **Strategist** — sees the broader picture
- **Researcher** — grounds responses in current information

Roles are assigned by task type, not fixed to models.
The council composition adapts to what the question requires.

### Sequential Build

Council members see what previous members said.
Each response builds on the last — not independent parallel
answers that the user must reconcile, but a genuine
conversation that arrives at synthesis.

The last response in the chain is the most informed response
in the session — it has seen everything that came before it.

### Adaptive Depth

Not every question needs the full council.
Simple question → single agent answers directly, fast.
Complex question → full council engages, builds, synthesises.

Same interface. Depth adapts to the question automatically.

---

## The Tribe System

Different task types require different council compositions:

- **Decide** — decision-focused specialists, devil's advocate mandatory
- **Research** — information gathering, source verification, synthesis
- **Create/Write** — generative specialists, editor, critic
- **Build** — technical specialists, architecture, security review
- **Analyse** — data interpretation, pattern recognition, challenge

The tribe is selected by task type. The council assembles
automatically. The user just asks the question.

---

## File Attachment as Context Layer

Any file — document, code, specification, research paper,
project brief — can be attached to a council session.
Every council member has read it before they speak.

No re-uploading per model. No re-explaining context.
The council is briefed once. Completely.

---

## Key Distinction from Existing Multi-Model Tools

Existing approaches:
- Show multiple model outputs side by side (user synthesises)
- Route to different models based on query type (still single model per query)
- Aggregate responses without specialist roles (no structure)

The AI Council:
- Sequential build where each model sees previous responses
- Defined specialist roles adapted to task type
- Synthesis happens in the session
- Single context shared across all models
- Depth adapts automatically to question complexity

---

## Prior Art Statement

To the best of the author's knowledge, no existing system
combines:

- Sequential multi-model build where each model sees
  previous responses
- Specialist role assignment adapted by task type (tribe system)
- Automatic depth adaptation (single agent vs full council)
- Shared context across all models without re-briefing
- Synthesis as a session output rather than a user task

in a unified architecture for AI-assisted decision making
and task completion.

This document establishes the date of conception and sufficient
technical detail to constitute prior art.

